<div style="padding:0px 0px 6px 0px"><table class="tborder" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center"><tr><td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" ><a name="post43559"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/tdg/statusicon/post_old.gif" alt="Old" border="0" /></a> 01-14-2003, 10:23 AM</td><td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" align="right">&nbsp;#<a href="showpost.php?s=0ae560748df707a3dc376beb25709ebc&amp;p=43559&amp;postcount=2" target="new"><strong>2</strong></a></td></tr><tr valign="top"><td class="alt2" width="175"><div id="postmenu_43559">Seriena</div><div class="smallfont">Guest</div><div class="smallfont">&nbsp;<br /><div>Posts: n/a</div><div>   </div></div></td><td class="alt1"><div><br /> Communication is huge. Don’t be afraid to ask or tell them up front to communicate with you on when it’s safe to heal. On raids, never heal a monk unless they say it’s ok. You either ask them “OK to heal?” or they tell you “Heal me”. The same rule generally applies to exp groups but to a lesser extent. If you are in a place that requires a lot of mob splitting then just don’t heal unless the monk is in camp fighting or they are fd. You will not gain agro if you heal a monk that is successfully feigned. If their fd fails and they are about to die….let them die. Death to a monk is not a big deal. In exp groups, just use your best judgment <br /></div></td></tr><tr><td class="alt2"> 	 &nbsp;</td><td class="alt1" align="right"><a href="newreply.php?s=0ae560748df707a3dc376beb25709ebc&amp;do=newreply&amp;p=43559"><img src="images/tdg/buttons/quote.gif" alt="Reply With Quote" border="0" /></a> 	</td></tr></table><div class="vbmenu_popup" id="postmenu_43559_menu" style="display:none"><table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"><tr><td class="thead">Seriena</td></tr></table></div></div>
