<div style="padding:0px 0px 6px 0px"><table class="tborder" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center"><tr><td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" ><a name="post43561"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/tdg/statusicon/post_old.gif" alt="Old" border="0" /></a> 01-14-2003, 12:04 PM</td><td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" align="right">&nbsp;#<a href="showpost.php?s=0ae560748df707a3dc376beb25709ebc&amp;p=43561&amp;postcount=4" target="new"><strong>4</strong></a></td></tr><tr valign="top"><td class="alt2" width="175"><div id="postmenu_43561">chenier</div><div class="smallfont">Guest</div><div class="smallfont">&nbsp;<br /><div>Posts: n/a</div><div>   </div></div></td><td class="alt1"><div><br /> When I'm main healing in an xp group with a monk, I always talk with the monk and let him/her know that I like to know when they use mend and when it's back up again. I think that monks then appreciate that I'm watching them carefully so that they don't have to use mend while fighting in camp (unless of course things get ugly) and can use it on pulls if needed.<br />
<br />
Or, I can run out and toss them a quick heal if they need it while their splitting and if they get owie.<br />
<br />
Anyway, communication is good. =) <br /></div></td></tr><tr><td class="alt2"> 	 &nbsp;</td><td class="alt1" align="right"><a href="newreply.php?s=0ae560748df707a3dc376beb25709ebc&amp;do=newreply&amp;p=43561"><img src="images/tdg/buttons/quote.gif" alt="Reply With Quote" border="0" /></a> 	</td></tr></table><div class="vbmenu_popup" id="postmenu_43561_menu" style="display:none"><table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"><tr><td class="thead">chenier</td></tr></table></div></div>
